# WORKFLOW RULESHEET

## Purpose
- Keep each session predictable: start clean, report progress clearly, close cleanly.
- Use this as the reusable backbone for future projects.

## Priority Order
1. Follow explicit user requests first.
2. If rules conflict, follow the more specific rule file.
3. Otherwise follow this workflow skeleton.

## Session Start
- Confirm the task in plain English before major work.
- Do quick context checks needed for the task type.
- For code work, verify repo state and key context files before edits.

## In-Session Updates
- Give short progress updates regularly during longer work.
- State what you are about to do before editing files.
- If blocked, explain the blocker and the next best option.

## Safe Change Rules
- Make the smallest change that solves the requested outcome.
- Do not revert unrelated user changes.
- Avoid destructive actions unless explicitly approved.

## Session Close
- Report what changed and why in plain English.
- List any follow-up checks or tests still needed.
- Confirm completion status against the requested scope.
- If a phase milestone was completed this session: update ROADMAP_TIMELINE.md — mark phase complete, record actual completion date, note any items that slipped to the next phase.
- If a phase milestone was completed this session: update ESTIMATION_RETROSPECTIVE.md and FORECAST_BASELINES.md — log safe vs actual delta and adjust forecast multipliers only when evidence supports it.

## Reuse Template (Copy to New Projects)
- Replace project name and path assumptions.
- Keep sections: Priority Order, Session Start, In-Session Updates, Safe Change Rules, Session Close.
- Add project-specific protocols in separate rule files, not in this skeleton.
